SIMPLE: monster
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Monster
<hw>Mon"ster</hw> <pr>(m⟦ocr⟧n*st⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>monstre</ets>, F. <ets>monstre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>monstrum</ets>,
orig., a divine omen, indicating misfortune; akin of
<ets>monstrare</ets> to show, point out, indicate, and <ets>monere</ets>
to warn. See <er>Monition</er>, and cf. <er>Demonstrate</er>,
<er>Muster</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something of unnatural size,
shape, or quality; a prodigy; an enormity; a marvel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>monster</qex> or marvel.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically , an animal or plant departing greatly
from the usual type, as by having too many limbs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any thing or person of unnatural or excessive
ugliness, deformity, wickedness, or cruelty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monster</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Monster
<hw>Mon"ster</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Monstrous in
size.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Enormous or very powerful; <as>as, he drove a
<ex>monster</ex> Harley</as>.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monster</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Monster
<hw>Mon"ster</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make monstrous.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monstera</ent>⟦br⟧
